  "Idea": "We propose a novel optimization architecture titled 'Dual-Space Adaptive Conditional Gradients' (DACG), which reimagines how global convex constraints are enforced in deep neural networks by decoupling primal representation learning from dual constraint regulation through a hierarchical, differentiable saddle-point formulation. Rather than modifying the feasible set during training—as in expressivity-guided expansion—DACG maintains a fixed base convex domain (e.g., nuclear norm balls, group-sparsity cones) but introduces a learnable dual coordinator network that modulates Lagrange multipliers associated with global constraints based on real-time violation trends and task-specific performance signals. The core innovation lies in replacing the standard Linear Minimization Oracle (LMO) of conditional gradients with a *differentiable dual oracle* (DDO): a lightweight neural module trained online to predict optimal dual variables that steer the next primal update toward lower constraint violation while preserving descent in loss. This DDO is implemented using a graph neural network (GNN) over the computational graph of the main model, where nodes represent parameter blocks and edges encode constraint couplings (e.g., spectral consistency across residual paths). The GNN outputs structured dual adjustments that are fed into a proximal conditional gradient step, effectively turning constraint enforcement into an adaptive feedback loop. Crucially, DACG retains O(1/t) convergence rates under stochastic settings by enforcing dual averaging with memory replay of past violations, extending theoretical results from Paper 2 to time-varying Lagrangian landscapes. Unlike post-hoc or penalty-based methods, DACG ensures persistent feasibility without requiring expensive projections or line searches. Furthermore, the framework supports compositional constraints—such as simultaneous robustness (via Lipschitz constraints), sparsity (via ℓ1,∞ norms), and algorithmic fairness (via convex demographic parity sets)—by instantiating multiple coordinated DDOs operating in parallel. We prove that under bounded gradient variance and uniform Slater conditions, DACG converges almost surely to a point satisfying both optimality and global constraints. Empirically, this enables stable training of deep architectures far beyond the NTK regime (validating Paper 1's expressivity condition dynamically) while achieving superior generalization and safety properties. Applications include certified adversarial robustness in Vision Transformers, fair representation learning in tabular models, and energy-constrained inference in mobile nets via rank-bounded updates. By integrating ideas from differentiable optimization, structured prediction, and constrained ML, DACG offers a scalable, theoretically sound pathway to trustworthy deep learning with built-in convex governance.",
